      "content": "hey, i'm trying to prototype a ray tracer in python and i'm struggling with the reflection math. can you write a function that takes an incident vector `i` and a surface normal `n` and returns the reflection vector `r`?\n\nthe vectors are just lists of floats. i need it to pass these tests i've got:\n\n```python\ndef test_reflection():\n    # test 1: simple 90 degree bounce\n    i1 = [1.0, -1.0, 0.0]\n    n1 = [0.0, 1.0, 0.0]\n    expected1 = [1.0, 1.0, 0.0]\n    assert reflection_vector(i1, n1) == expected1\n\n    # test 2: hitting a surface at an angle\n    i2 = [0.707, -0.707, 0.0]\n    n2 = [0.0, 1.0, 0.0]\n    expected2 = [0.707, 0.707, 0.0]\n    # using a small epsilon for float comparison\n    res2 = reflection_vector(i2, n2)\n    assert all(abs(a - b) < 1e-3 for a, b in zip(res2, expected2))\n\n    # test 3: hitting a side wall\n    i3 = [-1.0, 0.0, 0.0]\n    n3 = [1.0, 0.0, 0.0]\n    expected3 = [1.0, 0.0, 0.0]\n    assert reflection_vector(i3, n3) == expected3\n\nprint(\"tests passed!\")\n```\n\nlet me know when it's ready",
